english:
  title: Record of the Stone Pavilion
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Shin, known as Chang-bo, was a man of exceptional integrity and steadfast principle—the kind that cannot be shaken or taken away. Once he held high office at court and achieved great prominence, yet his unyielding righteousness offended the powerful ministers, and so he withdrew from public life to dwell in the countryside. By nature he loved stones. Whenever he ventured out and encountered an unusual stone, he would bring it home without delay. The largest he transported by cart, the next size by horse, smaller ones his servants carried on their backs, and the tiniest he tucked under his arm. Whatever his strength could bear, nothing was left behind.

    Angular stones and pointed stones, broad stones and narrow ones—scattered here and there, crisscrossing in every direction. Some possessed a dignified solidity and crystalline clarity, refined and majestic, bearing the virtue and bearing of a gentleman. Others were strange and wondrous, like recluse scholars dwelling in mountain mists. Still others stood upright and watchful, like loyal ministers who speak truth to power, discussing affairs of state with resolute countenance. Some gaped and jutted forth menacingly, like tigers and leopards in their fury. Others leapt and tumbled playfully, like lambs at their games. Some huddled close with heads touching and tails entwined, like schools of young fish moving as one. Such varieties were beyond counting.

    Master Shin gathered these stones and named his pavilion the Stone Pavilion. There he spent his days in repose. In summer, the wind fanned the air to coolness; in autumn, the moon shone with crystalline radiance. Flowers and grasses bloomed more beautifully; frost and snow grew more piercing. All of this was enhanced by the presence of the stones. Yet people know only that the Master loves stones—they do not understand why he loves them.

    The Book of Changes teaches: "When one's integrity is firm as stone, and virtue is maintained without ceasing, fortune is certain and auspicious." Is not the Master's steadfast principle, unshakeable and unbowed before power, the firmness of stone itself? His withdrawal from office to the countryside—is this not the ceasing of outward striving? His contentment found in the Way, free from unforeseen calamity—is this not the auspiciousness foretold? Perhaps the Master's joy springs from this very source. This is indeed worthy of recording.
  footnotes:
    - The reference to the Book of Changes (易經) draws on Hexagram 52 (艮), which deals with stillness and the virtue of knowing when to stop.
    - 'The Master''s love of stones operates on two levels: the literal collection of unusual rocks, and a deeper allegory for the virtue of steadfastness and immovability in the face of worldly pressures.'
